name: 3. Price Optimization using Optimization node
content:
Model Used

The Optimization Node is employed to systematically optimize pricing models. It supports multiple machine learning algorithms:

  • Random Forest: Provides robust performance, especially when capturing non-linear price-demand relationships.
  • Decision Tree: Offers interpretable decision rules, making it easier to explain pricing recommendations.

For each distinct product segment (e.g., SKU, product category, or region), a separate model is built to capture unique pricing dynamics.

Features Details

The models incorporate both internal and external drivers of demand, including:

  • Product-related: Product pack price, SKU, size.
  • Competitive landscape: Competitor prices across multiple brands.
  • Promotional drivers: Advertising spend, events, BAU (business-as-usual), fleeting promotions, SVD.
  • Seasonality and time effects: Year-week, quarter indicators, monthly splits.

Feature Importance

Feature importance is determined differently for each algorithm:

  • Tree-based models (Random Forest, Decision Tree): Use Gini importance, permutation importance, or SHAP values.
  • The system stores the most relevant predictors for each model, allowing users to identify key price and non-price factors that influence sales.



Model Metrics

The Optimization Node evaluates models using configurable loss metrics aligned with business goals, such as:

  • MAE (Mean Absolute Error): Measures average prediction error in units sold.
  • RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error): Penalizes larger deviations in sales forecasts.
  • Mean Percentage Error: Highlights relative prediction accuracy, useful for comparing across SKUs of different scales.


Model Selection and Storage

  • The best-performing model for each distinct product segment is selected based on the lowest chosen loss metric.
  • Final model details (configuration parameters, feature importances, validation results) are stored for future use.
  • Visualizations such as revenue parabolas are generated, overlaying demand curves for multiple SKUs to illustrate elasticity and revenue optimization opportunities.



Revenue Parabolas and Demand Forecasting

  • After iterating over all distinct values, a visualization is created to overlay revenue parabolas for all SKUs.
  • This consolidated view provides insights into demand elasticity and enables informed forecasting decisions.


Benefits :

  • Enhanced Decision-Making: By iterating over distinct values, the system generates tailored pricing recommendations for each SKU or segment.
  • Scalable Framework: Supports a variety of machine learning methods and customizable configurations, making it adaptable to different business needs.
  • Comprehensive Visualizations: The revenue parabola overlay provides a concise summary of pricing impacts across all SKUs, enabling strategic demand forecasting.
